Events.RelatedDescription: Closed issue "[Service degradation] Package download counts are delayed" (#9018) at NuGet/NuGetGallery
Events.RelatedBody:
As mentioned in NuGet.org's [status page](https://status.nuget.org/):

> **Package download statistics are delayed. Download logs have been processed up to February 11th, 2022.** Download count statistics are currently being ingested at a reduced rate. This is resulting in download counts on packages not reflecting their latest status. We apologize for the inconvenience and are actively working on a solution.
>
> Our current plan forward is to accelerate our migration to a new statistics pipeline which will help us overcome the scaling issues that we have encountered.

To provide a bit more context: our team has been using a SQL-based statistics data warehouse solution which has had more and more scaling issues over the years. We have been working for several months on a new solution based on [Azure Synapse Analytics](https://azure.microsoft.com/en-us/services/synapse-analytics/) which will help us overcome the growing volume of download logs that we process.

The download logs are processed in order for use to generate various statistics reports (most notably the total download counts showing in many UI experiences). This new Synapse-based infrastructure will also allow us to more easily add new reports and statistics features in the future as well as keep up with the wonderful growth of the .NET ecosystem.

The old pipeline began to fall behind on log ingestion in mid-January before our planned migration to the new pipeline had completed. This was a surprise to us. Fortunately, our new pipeline is not far off from being ready for production usage. There were some remaining steps of hardening the monitoring as well and log reflow edge cases that we wanted complete prior turning off the old pipeline and activating the new one. To avoid investing engineering effort into the older stats pipeline (essentially throwaway work), we chose to focus our efforts on the migration to the new pipeline.

We anticipate during the next week or two (week of February 28th or March 6th) to have these final stabilization steps for the new pipeline completed and the reports produced by the new pipeline (i.e. parity with existing behavior on the old pipeline) to be activated on NuGet.org.

In the interim, you will continue to see delayed download counts as the old pipeline stoically churns to through a big pile of log files. No download counts have been lost and we anticipate the new pipeline to quickly churn through the backlog of logs at a satisfactory rate.

When the issue is resolved, we will clear the status page and close this issue.

Events.RelatedDescription: Closed issue "[Bug]: Different package resolved with invalid version" (#11417) at NuGet/Home
Events.RelatedBody:
### NuGet Product Used

NuGet.exe, Visual Studio Package Management UI

### Product Version

NuGet Version: 5.6.0.6591, Visual Studio 16.11.5 with NuGet Package Manager 5.11.0

### Worked before?

No

### Impact

It's more difficult to complete my work

### Repro Steps & Context

So, really weird problem here. No idea how that can be or why it happens with this specific package. It's an internal package unfortunately so I have to change names, but I'll try to add as much information as possible and keep names consistent.  
(csproj-) Code Samples will be copypasted and then anonymised. Versions will be shortened from things like 1.23.4567.123456 to 1.23 for simplicity.  
I hope you can help me solve this, I'm very confused with this.

**Short version**: We use LibX version 2.62 and LibY version 2.67 (completely different libraries), NuGet restore says it can't find LibX version 2.67 after changing to PackageReference.

**Long version** (Smaller, possibly more isolated case below):

So OurProduct is currently being updated to .NET Framework 4.7.2 and PackageReference. Before, it was on n462 and used \<Reference> everywhere.   
Several projects in one solution, one big one tying everything together. That one also uses libraries provided by other, internal teams.

One of those libraries is InternalLibX. We use version 2.62 so the \<Reference> looked like this:

    <Reference Include="InternalLibX, Version=2.62, Culture=neutral, processorArchitecture=MSIL">
      <HintPath>..\..\packages\InternalLibX.2.62\lib\net451\InternalLibX.dll</HintPath>
    </Reference>

Another library is InternalLibY. We use version 2.67 so the \<Reference> looked like this:

    <Reference Include="InternalLibY, Version=2.67, Culture=neutral, processorArchitecture=MSIL">
      <HintPath>..\..\packages\InternalLibY.7\lib\net451\InternalLibY.dll</HintPath>
    </Reference>

Now I changed it to use PackageReference like this:

    <PackageReference Include="InternalLibX" Version="2.62" />
    <PackageReference Include="InternalLibY">
      <Version>2.67</Version>
    </PackageReference>

And the NuGet restore now gives me first a warning and then fails the restore with the following message:

    Errors in C:\Sources\OurProduct\api\OurProduct\OurProduct.csproj
          NU1603: OurProduct depends on InternalLibX(>= 2.67) but InternalLibX 2.67 was not found. An approximate best match of InternalLibX 2.62 was resolved.

Which really doesn't make any sense, since nobody says that we need InternalLibY of version 2.67, which also doesn't even exist. It hasn't been built. I scanned the csproj file again and there is no mention of it. The only occurrence of that not found version is in InternalLibX.

On top of that, InternalLibY isn't found in the code. The restore says it finds InternalLibY version 2.67 and adds it to the packages folder, no mention of problems with the restore here. Yet when referencing it in the code ("using InternalLibY;") it says "Cannot resolve symbol InternalLibY", crashing the whole party.

I'd be ok with the warning being ignored and the resolved version being used (because it is the correct one), but instead of just a warning the restore just fails.

This same problem also happens with another, smaller project in this solution, exactly the same setup with exactly the same restore errors except here the InternalLibY isn't imported with "using InternalLibY" but used like "InternalLibY.Tools.CheckThisValue(someInput)" and there it cannot be resolved.

**Smaller, possibly more isolated case**:

As you can see in the logs, there is another, similar problem, that looks smaller:

    NU1603: InternalLibP 2.231 depends on Company.small.sub.lib (>= 1.6) but Company.small.sub.lib 1.6 was not found. An approximate best match of Company.small.sub.lib 1.13 was resolved.

Which makes no sense again - **InternalLibP 2.231 references Company.small.sub.lib 1.13**, which is exactly what is resolved as "approximate best match".  
I tried adding Company.small.sub.lib 1.13 as a PackageReference to our own project to maybe workaround this, but the same happens. No Idea where 1.6 comes from, our csproj has no mention of that version. I'm hoping this one is solved with the main problem, but it may be a simpler case to trace. 

I will include the log of running nuget restore on the whole solution executed from command line. I anonymised it using find+replace, hope it worked fine everywhere. 

Tell me if you need any more information, I will gladly provide anything that could help solve this.

Events.RelatedDescription: Opened issue "[Feature]: Add support for a dedicated environment variable providing the NuGetScratch path." (#11671) at NuGet/Home
Events.RelatedBody:
### NuGet Product(s) Involved

MSBuild.exe

### The Elevator Pitch

It would allow us to run multiple builds on the same CI server where:

1. Each build has its own TEMP directory pointing at the build staging directory
2. All the builds would be able to share the same NuGetScratch directory.

This way all the garbage files created by the unit tests in the temp directory are automatically deleted before the next build and all the concurrently running nuget processes can still synchronize between themselves.

Events.RelatedBody:
At Unity, we would like to explore the possibility of having a new target framework moniker for a very small base class library profile that Unity will use for some of its products.

This profile will focus on a few principles:
* Small code size
* No support for reflection
* Focus on value types
* Limited GC allocations
* Limited use of exceptions
* Limited use of virtual methods

We would like to make this profile available on NuGet so that it can be used in .csproj files to allow good IDE integration and to allow developers to write libraries using it.

This profile will be a proper subset for .NET Standard 2.0, and later a proper subset of .NET 5.

Initially, I'll propose the name "unity2.0-dots", to indicate that it is a proper subset of .NET Standard 2.0.

Let's discuss whether or not this is a good idea, and if it something that can be implemented.

Events.RelatedDescription: Closed issue "[Bug]: Warning about ignoring VersionOverride assumes that no other central package management is in use" (#11662) at NuGet/Home
Events.RelatedBody:
### NuGet Product Used

dotnet.exe, MSBuild.exe, NuGet.exe

### Product Version

17.2 Preview 2

### Worked before?

17.2 Preview 1

### Impact

I'm unable to use this version

### Repro Steps & Context

Originally reported by @andygerlicher

1. Use `Microsoft.Build.CentralPackageVersions`
2. Specify `VersionOverride` on a `<PackageReference />`
3. Update to Visual Studio 17.2 Preview 2

Restore will log a warning:
```
C:\src\foo\foo.csproj : warning NU1504: The package reference Something specifies a VersionOverride but central package manageent is currently disabled so the value was ignored. [C:\src\foo\foo.csproj]
```

NuGet's central package management assumes that if its disabled, the user has no other reason to use `VersionOverride` metadata.  We'll need to remove this warning until we can find a good way to determine if the user would need to see this warning.

The only workaround is to suppress the warning.
